Spotify EDA of Personal Music Taste¶

Every year, Spotify releases a 'Spotify Wrapped' tailored to each user's listening experience. But they only release so much information to the user and it got me curious about the ins and outs of my own music listening history.

Spotipy Initalization¶

In order to perform exploratory data analysis (EDA), I need to gather the saved songs from my spotify library. Saved songs are classified as those that received a 'like' which is in the shape of a heart on Spotify.

I achieve this using a Spotipy which is a python library for the Spotify API

Note: if you're interested in using either of these yourself, you can see my resources_and_setup file

In [5]:
token = spotipy.util.prompt_for_user_token(sp_username, scope)

# make sure that username token exists
if token:
    spotipy_obj = spotipy.Spotify(auth=token)
    saved_tracks_resp = spotipy_obj.current_user_saved_tracks(limit=50)
else:
    print('Couldn\'t get token for that username')
    
# get the total number of tracks in my 'liked songs'
number_of_tracks = saved_tracks_resp['total']
print('%d tracks' % number_of_tracks)

# select which features to get
def save_only_some_fields(track_response):
    return {        
        'id': str(track_response['track']['id']),
        'name': str(track_response['track']['name']),
        'artists': [artist['name'] for artist in track_response['track']['artists']],
        'duration_ms': track_response['track']['duration_ms'],
        'popularity': track_response['track']['popularity'],
        'added_at': track_response['added_at']
    }

# create a list of the tracks in my 'liked songs'
tracks = [save_only_some_fields(track) for track in saved_tracks_resp['items']]

# iterate through tracks list 
while saved_tracks_resp['next']:
    saved_tracks_resp = spotipy_obj.next(saved_tracks_resp)
    tracks.extend([save_only_some_fields(track) for track in saved_tracks_resp['items']])

4677 tracks

Add Audio Features¶

In [9]:
# create an empty dictionary for the audio features
audio_features = {}

# for the ids in our dataset, find the audio feature values
for idd in liked_songs['id'].tolist():
    audio_features[idd] = spotipy_obj.audio_features(idd)[0]

# create new columns acousticness, speechiness, key, etc to represent the audio features
# with the applied values for each song
liked_songs['acousticness'] = liked_songs['id'].apply(lambda idd: audio_features[idd]['acousticness'])
liked_songs['speechiness'] = liked_songs['id'].apply(lambda idd: audio_features[idd]['speechiness'])
liked_songs['key'] = liked_songs['id'].apply(lambda idd: str(audio_features[idd]['key']))
liked_songs['liveness'] = liked_songs['id'].apply(lambda idd: audio_features[idd]['liveness'])
liked_songs['instrumentalness'] = liked_songs['id'].apply(lambda idd: audio_features[idd]['instrumentalness'])
liked_songs['energy'] = liked_songs['id'].apply(lambda idd: audio_features[idd]['energy'])
liked_songs['tempo'] = liked_songs['id'].apply(lambda idd: audio_features[idd]['tempo'])
liked_songs['time_signature'] = liked_songs['id'].apply(lambda idd: audio_features[idd]['time_signature'])
liked_songs['loudness'] = liked_songs['id'].apply(lambda idd: audio_features[idd]['loudness'])
liked_songs['danceability'] = liked_songs['id'].apply(lambda idd: audio_features[idd]['danceability'])
liked_songs['valence'] = liked_songs['id'].apply(lambda idd: audio_features[idd]['valence'])

Add Genres¶

In [11]:
# define the function to search for the genre per artist
def get_genres(artist, spotipy_obj):
    response = spotipy_obj.search(q='artist:' + artist, type='artist')['artists']['items']
    return response[0]['genres'] if response else []
In [12]:

Add in Pitch Classes¶

We currently have the key of each song, but we don't know what that really means. Let's add in their corresponding pitch classes

In [144]:
liked_songs['key'] = liked_songs['key'].astype('str')
In [122]:
# create pitch class dictionary
pitch_classes = {'0':'C/Do', '1':'C#/Do sost.', '2':'D/Re', '3':'D/Re sost.', '4':'E/Mi', '5':'F/Fa', '6':'F#/Fa sost.', '7':'G/Sol', '8':'G#/Sol sost.', '9':'A/La', '10':'A#/La sost.', '11':'B/Si'}

liked_songs['pitch_class'] = liked_songs['artists'].map(pitch_classes)

In [108]:
liked_songs_clean.shape
Out[108]:
(4677, 20)

There are 4677 rows and 19 columns in this dataset. That's a lot of songs!

This already brings up some questions:

  1. what do all of these columns mean?
  2. what is the range of these columns
  3. how many songs did I add per year?
  4. am I more likely to add songs at a particular time of day? on a particular day/month/year?
  5. how many songs per artist?
  6. which genre/artist do I listen to the most?
  7. do I the songs I listen to tend to be more popular or less?
  8. how many songs do I listen to that have the same name?
  9. is there a pattern to the audio features?

We've got some gears turning here. Let's start with the first two. We can use liked_songs_clean.describe and the Spotify API dashboard to create a table of our columns names and a brief description.

Visualization¶

Now that we've done some initial exploring, we'll create some visuals.

Heatmap for correlation between variables¶

In [204]:
# create heatmap for correlation
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
corr = liked_songs_clean.corr()
sns.heatmap(corr, annot=True, cmap="coolwarm").set_title('Pearson correlation matrix')
plt.show()

Correlation values range from -1 to 1. The closer a correlation value is to 1 (positive or negative), the stronger the correlation between the two variables. Variables with a strong positive correlation increase together, whereas variables with a strong negative correlation experience opposing polarization (as one goes up, the other goes down and vice versa). The closer the correlation is to 0, the weaker the correlation.

  • variables will always have a correlation of 1 with themselves
  • we can see the strongest correlation is between energy and acousticness at -0.8.
  • the weakest correlation is between speechiness and dat at -0.00036

Overall, none of our variables are very strongly correlated.

How have the audio features of my song choices changed over time? We can write a time series function to plot the change of our data over timie

In [238]:
def plot_time_series(col_name, title, rolling_window_days):
    daily_series = pd.Series(data=np.array(liked_songs_clean[col_name]), 
                                      name=col_name, 
                                      index=liked_songs_clean['added_at']).sort_index()

    (daily_series.rolling(window = rolling_window_days)
     .mean()
     .plot(figsize=(30, 10))
     .set(xlabel='date (by day)', ylabel=col_name, title=title))

    plt.show()
In [239]:
plot_time_series('popularity', 'Popularity over time (window = 30 days)', 30)
plot_time_series('duration_s', 'Duration (s) over time (window = 30 days)', 30)
plot_time_series('danceability', 'Danceability over time (window = 30 days)', 30)
plot_time_series('valence', 'Valence over time (window = 30 days)', 30)
plot_time_series('energy', 'Energy over time (window = 30 days)', 30)
plot_time_series('tempo', 'Tempo over time (window = 30 days)', 30)
